          "body": "Verses 9-11 set two trajectories in sharpest contrast. *Those who want (*boulomai* — willed, deliberate desire) to be rich fall into temptation and a snare* (6:9). The verbs trace the descent — they *fall* (*empipto*), they are *plunged* (*buthizo*, the verb for sinking a ship), they wander *from the faith*, they *pierce themselves through* with many sorrows (*peripeiro* — to impale). Paul's language is violent because the trajectory is violent: it ends in *olethros kai apoleia* — ruin and destruction (6:9). The man of God, by contrast, *flees* (*pheugo*) and *pursues* (*dioko*) — the same verb-pair Paul uses elsewhere of fleeing sexual sin (2 Tim 2:22). Six virtues are named as the pursuit's object (6:11): righteousness, godliness, faith, love, perseverance, gentleness. The Christian life is not neutrality; it is a directional choice between two pursuits."
